const description = 'Frequently asked questions about burn injury claims: settlement timing, reconstructive surgery, life-care planning, insurance, attorney fees, and more.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>

  <h2>How much is a burn injury case worth?</h2>
  <p>Highly dependent on burn depth, TBSA, body location, liability strength, defendant insurance, and jurisdiction. Rough ranges: minor burns under 5% TBSA $25K&ndash;$150K; moderate 2nd&ndash;3rd degree 10&ndash;25% TBSA $250K&ndash;$1.5M; severe 25&ndash;50% TBSA $1M&ndash;$5M; catastrophic over 50% TBSA or with airway involvement $3M&ndash;$15M+; fatal $1M&ndash;$10M+ in wrongful death. Face, hand, genital, and airway burns carry separate multipliers because of disfigurement and functional impact. See our <a href="/">calculator</a> for an estimate based on case specifics.</p>

  <h2>How long does a burn injury case take?</h2>
  <p>Typically 18&ndash;36 months from injury to final resolution. Severe burn cases often run longer because reconstructive surgery sequencing &mdash; and the resulting damages picture &mdash; takes 12&ndash;24 months to clarify. Most cases don't settle until scar maturation is reasonably advanced and the reconstructive-surgery roadmap is well-defined.</p>

  <h2>Do I have to pay the attorney up front?</h2>
  <p>No. Burn-injury attorneys typically work on contingency (33&ndash;40% of recovery) with no out-of-pocket cost to the client. The attorney advances case costs (experts, depositions, exhibits, life-care planner fees, burn-medicine experts) and is reimbursed from recovery.</p>

  <h2>Why does my burn case involve so many experts?</h2>
  <p>Catastrophic burn cases typically retain: a burn-medicine expert (often a burn-center attending) for causation and prognosis, a plastic and reconstructive surgeon for projected procedure list, a certified life care planner for cost projection, an economist for present-value calculation and lost-earnings analysis, a vocational rehabilitation expert for residual earning capacity, a psychologist for PTSD and body-image impact, and sometimes a fire-cause or product-defect expert for liability. Each is paid by the attorney and reimbursed from recovery.</p>

  <h2>What if the at-fault party has no insurance?</h2>
  <p>Other recovery sources may apply: your own homeowners' or renters' insurance (for some accidental burns), your auto policy's UM/UIM coverage (if a vehicle was involved), the at-fault party's employer (if working at the time), product manufacturers (if a defective product contributed), and government entities (where applicable, with special notice procedures). An experienced burn-injury attorney identifies all potential sources.</p>

  <h2>How is "future medical care" calculated for burns?</h2>
  <p>A certified life care planner with burn-specific experience itemizes projected reconstructive surgeries, scar treatment (laser, steroid injections, pressure garments), therapy, psychiatric care, and skin/wound care year by year through expected lifespan. For severe burns the planner often projects 20+ reconstructive procedures over 5&ndash;10 years post-injury, plus indefinite scar and skin-care maintenance. An economist then reduces these costs to present value.</p>

  <h2>Are disfigurement damages a separate category?</h2>
  <p>Yes, in most states. Disfigurement is treated as a damages category distinct from general pain-and-suffering. Valuation depends on visibility (face, hands, neck command the largest awards), severity, age (younger claimants face longer lives with the scar), and (in some cases) occupation. Disfigurement awards in moderate-to-severe burn cases commonly fall $200K&ndash;$2M+.</p>

  <h2>Is my burn injury settlement taxable?</h2>
  <p>Compensatory damages for physical injury are excluded from taxable income under IRC &sect; 104(a)(2). Punitive damages and certain other components may be taxable. Consult a tax professional for specific situations.</p>

  <h2>Should I take a structured settlement or lump sum?</h2>
  <p>Depends on case-specific factors. Structured settlements provide guaranteed periodic payments and tax advantages; lump sums offer flexibility but require careful long-term financial management for cases where reconstructive needs span many years. Many burn settlements use a combination &mdash; lump sum for immediate needs (home modifications, lost wages caught up) and structured payments timed to expected future reconstructive surgeries. Discuss with your attorney and a financial advisor.</p>

  <h2>What is TBSA and why does it matter?</h2>
  <p>Total Body Surface Area &mdash; the percentage of body skin affected by 2nd-degree or deeper burns. It drives medical resuscitation, life-care plan complexity, and case valuation. Most burn centers use the Lund-Browder chart for an accurate TBSA estimate; the Rule of Nines is used in the field for quick assessment. Make sure your records reflect a Lund-Browder TBSA rather than a field estimate alone.</p>

  <h2>Can I keep my SSDI/Medicaid after settlement?</h2>
  <p>Possibly, with a special needs trust. Settlement proceeds placed in a properly structured special needs trust do not disqualify the recipient from means-tested benefits. Your attorney should coordinate with a special needs attorney for any settlement large enough to threaten benefits eligibility.</p>

  <h2>What if I was partially at fault?</h2>
  <p>Most states have comparative negligence rules. Pure comparative negligence (California, Florida): you can recover even if mostly at fault, reduced by your percentage. Modified comparative negligence (most states): you can recover if less than 50% (or 51%) at fault, reduced by your percentage. A handful of states still have contributory negligence (DC, Maryland, Virginia, Alabama, North Carolina) where any fault on your part bars recovery. In burn cases, common partial-fault issues include consumer misuse of products (which manufacturers raise as defense), worker safety-procedure violations, and intoxication.</p>

  <h2>More questions?</h2>
